ngland":"Rye, Sussex, England","Downe, Kent, England":"Downe, Kent, England"},"cs":{"about 1330–":"okolo 1330–Zesnulý","1353–1425":"1353–1425","1330–Male":"1330–Zesnulý","1337":"1337","1425":"1425","1453":"1453","1353":"1353","1330":"1330","1382":"1382","about 1330":"okolo 1330","Rye, Sussex, England":"Rye, Sussex, Anglie","Downe, Kent, England":"Downe, Kent, Anglie"},"da":{"about 1330–":"omkring 1330–Afdød","1353–1425":"1353–1425","1330–Male":"1330–Afdød","1337":"1337","1425":"1425","1453":"1453","1353":"1353","1330":"1330","1382":"1382","about 1330":"omkring 1330","Rye, Sussex, England":"Rye, Sussex, England","Downe, Kent, England":"Downe, Kent, England"},"nl":{"about 1330–":"circa 1330–Overleden","1353–1425":"1353–1425","1330–Male":"1330–Overleden","1337":"1337","1425":"1425","1453":"1453","1353":"1353","1330":"1330","1382":"1382","about 1330":"circa 1330","Rye, Sussex, England":"Rye, Sussex, England","Downe, Kent, England":"Downe, Kent, England"},"en":{"about 1330–":"about 1330–Deceased","1353–1425":"1353–1425","1330–Male":"1330–Deceased","1337":"1337","1425":"1425","1453":"1453","1353":"1353","1330":"1330","1382":"1382","about 1330":"about 1330","Rye, Sussex, England":"Rye, Sussex, England","Downe, Kent, England":"Downe, Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rolfe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, from the Middle English and Anglo-Norman French personal name <i>Rolf</i>, <i>Roulf</i>, <i>Rou</i>, <i>Roul</i>, <i>Rouf</i>, <i>Rof</i>. Its usual derivation is from Old Norse <i>Hrólfr</i>, <i>Rolf</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame, renown’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’, and occasionally from ancient Germanic <i>Rodulf</i>, of the same origin as <i>Hrólfr</i> (earlier <i>Hróthúlfr</i>) but in a West Frankish form, which the Scandinavian Normans occasionally used. The name was also common in Normandy where it became Old French <i>Roul</i>, <i>Rou</i>, often Latinized as <i>Rollo</i>. See   Ralph   and compare   Rowe  ,   Dow  , and   Rowson  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Rolph","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, a variant of   Rolfe  ."]},{"name":"Rolf","meanings":["English: variant of   Rolfe  .","North German: from a personal name, a shortened form of   Rudolf  ."]},{"name":"Roof","meanings":["English: variant of   Rolfe  .","English: variant of   Ruff  .","German: from <i>Ruffo</i>, a short form of an ancient Germanic personal name formed with <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame, renown’. This surname is very rare in Germany."]},{"name":"Ralph","meanings":["English: from Anglo-Norman and Middle English <i>Raulf</i>, <i>Ralf</i>, an Old French form of ancient Germanic <i>Radulf</i> (from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel, advice’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’), hence the usual latinization of the name as <i>Radulfus</i>. <i>Ralph</i> was a common personal name among the Normans and from the mid 13th century among the native English. Almost 7% of men in the late 14th century were named <i>Ralph</i>. It was pronounced in a variety of ways, giving rise to a large number of different surnames. <i>Ralf</i> could be shortened to <i>Raff</i>, hence the surname   Raff   and possibly   Raffel  . <i>Raulf</i> was sometimes shortened to <i>Raul</i>, giving us   Rall   and <b>Rawlin</b> (see   Rawling  ). It also appears as <i>Rauf</i>, which was often shortened to <i>Rau</i>, hence the surnames   Rawe   and <b>Rawkin</b> (‘young Ralph’), as well as   Haw  ,   Hawkins  ,   Daw   and   Dawkins  , derived from rhyming pet forms. In late Middle English the diphthong <i>-au-</i> was sometimes simplified to long <i>-a-</i>, later pronounced ‘ay’ as in modern English <i>day</i>, which accounts for <b>Rafe</b>. This pronunciation of the personal name <i>Ralph</i> is still occasionally found in modern times. <i>Ralph</i> is a learned spelling of <i>Ralf</i> that became common in the 16th century. In Anglo-Norman and Middle English usage, the rarer personal name <i>Rolf</i> was sometimes confused with <i>Ralf</i>, which explains why <i>Ralf</i> is an alternative source for   Rolf  ,   Rowe  ,   Dow  , and their derivatives."]},{"name":"Roffe","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Gady, Hyman.","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Rolfe  .","English: variant of   Roff   or   Rough  ."]},{"name":"Rolston","meanings":["English (Leicestershire):","habitational name either from Rolleston (Leicestershire, Nottinghamshire, Staffordshire) and perhaps Rowston (Lincolnshire), Rolston (or Rowlston) in Mappleton (East Yorkshire), or from Rollestone in Upton Pyne, or Rolstone Barton in Morchard Bishop (both in Devon), or Rollestone (Wiltshire), and perhaps Rowlestone (Herefordshire) or Rolstone in Banwell (Somerset). The placenames have various etymological origins, though most are named with the Middle English personal name <i>Rolf</i> or the Old Norse personal name <i>Hrólfr</i> + Middle English <i>toun</i> ‘town, settlement’, Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. See   Rolfe  .","variant of   Rollison  , shortened to <i>Rolleson</i> and altered by the addition of an intrusive <i>-t-</i>, as though it were a habitational name in <i>-ston</i>."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":7,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":52,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"John Rolfe was born about 1330, in Rye, Sussex, England. He had at least 1 daughter. He died in Downe, Kent, England."},"et":{"about 1330–":"umbes 1330–Surnud","1353–1425":"1353–1425","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1337":"1337","1425":"1425","1453":"1453","1353":"1353","1330":"1330","1382":"1382","about 1330":"umbes 1330","Rye, Sussex, England":"Rye, Sussex, England","Downe, Kent, England":"Downe, Kent, England"},"fi":{"about 1330–":"noin 1330–Kuollut","1353–1425":"1353–1425","1330–Male":"1330–Kuollut","1337":"1337","1425":"1425","1453":"1453","1353":"1353","1330":"1330","1382":"1382","about 1330":"noin 1330","Rye, Sussex, England":"Rye, Sussex, England","Downe, Kent, England":"Downe, Kent, England"},"fr":{"about 1330–":"environ 1330–Décédé","1353–1425":"1353–1425","1330–Male":"1330–Décédé","1337":"1337","1425":"1425","1453":"1453","1353":"1353","1330":"1330","1382":"1382","about 1330":"environ 1330","Rye, Sussex, England":"Rye, Sussex, Angleterre","Downe, Kent, England":"Downe, Kent, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"John Rolfe est né environ 1330, à Rye, Sussex, Angleterre. Il a eu au moins 1 fille. Il est décédé à Downe, Kent, Angleterre."},"de":{"about 1330–":"um 1330–Verstorben","1353–1425":"1353–1425","1330–Male":"1330–Verstorben","1337":"1337","1425":"1425","1453":"1453","1353":"1353","1330":"1330","1382":"1382","about 1330":"um 1330","Rye, Sussex, England":"Rye, Sussex, England","Downe, Kent, England":"Downe, Kent, England","lifeSummary":"John Rolfe wurde um 1330 in Rye, Sussex, England geboren. Er hatte mindestens 1 Tochter. Er starb in Downe, Kent, England."},"ht":{"about 1330–":"about 1330–Desede","1353–1425":"1353–1425","1330–Male":"1330–Desede","1337":"1337","1425":"1425","1453":"1453","1353":"1353","1330